contact/\">contact me</a>.','Investing','','publish','closed','open','','investing','','','2013-01-23 22:17:23','2013-01-24 03:17:23','',0,'http://localhost/teddy/?page_id=8',0,'page','',0),(9,1,'2013-01-22 22:26:04','2013-01-23 03:26:04','The average Torontonian enters less than 10 condos or lofts a year. People who don’t work in real estate, especially outside of the condo and loft market, know very little about the condos and lofts in Toronto, regardless of the open houses they have strolled through or the “research they’ve conducted online.”\r\n\r\nWhile listings can provide you with basic information about a property like the price, maintenance fees and property taxes - you may not be able to interpret vital information contained in a listing sheet. Additionally, you can’t compare a listing to other units in a building effectively without knowing the layout of the building, future development plans around the building and knowledge of past sales in the building and surrounding neighborhood.\r\n\r\nListings are too frequently misleading to prospective buyers and sellers.\r\n\r\nTo learn how to use listings as the powerful tool they are, <a title=\"Contact\" href=\"http://localhost/teddy/contact/\">contact me</a>.','Listings','','publish','closed','open','','listings','','','2013-01-23 22:18:08','2013-01-24 03:18:08','',0,'http://localhost/teddy/?page_id=9',0,'page','',0),(10,1,'2013-01-22 22:26:21','2013-01-23 03:26:21','Renting a place for 2-3 years is an excellent way to spend $40,000-$80,000K and have nothing but a bunch of U-Haul boxes and some packing tape at the end of occupancy to show for it.\r\n\r\nObviously, if you can’t afford a condo or loft, you still need a roof over your head and renting is the best viable option, next to a friend’s couch.\r\n\r\nHowever, if you’re going to rent to “learn about the area before you buy” or to “see where the market goes” you have a lack of market knowledge which only helps wealthy people stay wealthy.\r\n\r\nIf you’